textAfterTable: 11 Songs Editors’ Notes Vacillating between strutting, future-disco jams (“Bullet in the Brain”, “Year in Review”) and soulful synth-driven rockers (“10 Lovers”, “Fever”), Turn Blue is unified by singer/guitarist Dan Auerbach’s passionate songwriting, a brooding, ghostly atmosphere and the enduring power—and flexibility—of the blues. Customer Reviews An Album with an Identity Crisis           by SomeHowe Before I get into this, I wan't to make clear I like this album, and more importantly, I love this band I don't think they have made a single bad album and I don't think this album is their first. However, this album is nowhere near perfect. The fact of the matter is, this is an album that has no clue what it wants to be. Sometimes it's pshychedelic, sometimes it's synth-rock, and sometimes it's a weird mish-mash of the two with some old blues-rock flourishes. This makes the album overall very inconsistant, and the songs are no different. Without a clear cohesive sound, everything just falls apart at places.
